article.headline: Tulane 70, Ark.-Pine Bluff 68
article.story: NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Matt Wheaton's rebound and put-back with just one second remaining gave Tulane a 70-68 victory over Arkansas-Pine Bluff on Friday. Tulane (6-4) rallied on several occasions against the Golden Lions (2-9), who led at the half, 30-28. Wheaton's free throw with 53 seconds remaining tied the game at 68-68. The Green Wave applied pressure and UAPB had to settle for a rushed 3-pointer from the top of the key by Larry Williams for its lone attempt to win the game with 15 seconds on the clock. Robinson Louisme grabbed the missed shot and Tulane called time-out, setting up Wheaton's last second heroics. When Tulane in-bounded the ball, Chris Moore's open attempt with four seconds left fell short and Wheaton was in the right place to corral the rebound and bank a shot off the backboard with just a second left in the game. David Gomez led four Tulane players into double figure scoring with 16 points, while Kevin Sims and Louisme added 12 points apiece. Wheaton finished with 10 points, all of which came during the final half. Marcelle Goins led all scorers with 21 points for Arkansas-Pine Bluff, while William Byrd added 19 to the Golden Gophers. Tulane shot 44.8 percent from the field for the game, compared to 43.5 percent for UAPB.
